<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-09-15T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-09-15T08:00:00-05:00" n="339" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d339">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">868.48/99: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>)
                                <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-15T16:00:00+03:00"><hi rend="italic">September 15,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September 15
                                (16?)—3:10 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>186. Following from Smyrna repeated for the Department’s information:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“14th. Recommend Allies be urged to bring strong pressure to bear
                                    on Greece forcing her to accept refugees in Thrace or Macedonia.
                                    Conduct of Greek troops during retreat has rendered their
                                    locating in Asia Minor impossible. At same time immediate
                                    decision should be requested regarding transportation via Allied
                                    warships and transports, estimated number 300,000. Hepburn.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>